Step 1: Clean Data

folder = 'InauguralSpeeches/'
file_list = dir(folder)
read_folder <- function(infolder) {
  data_frame(file = dir(infolder, full.names = TRUE)) %>%
    mutate(text = map(file, read_lines)) %>%
    transmute(id = basename(file), text) %>%
    unnest(text)
}
# Read the folder
raw_text <- read_folder(folder)
#Merge the text with president information
extract <- function(word){
  substring(word,6,nchar(word)-6)
}
t <- function(word){
  substring(word, nchar(word)-4, nchar(word)-4)
}
raw_text$File = sapply(raw_text$id, extract)
raw_text$Term = sapply(raw_text$id, t)
dates <- read.csv("InauguationDates.txt",header=T, sep="")
info <- read.csv("InaugurationInfo.csv")
data_frame <- merge(raw_text,info, by=c("File","Term"),all.x=TRUE,all.y=TRUE)

Step 2: Comparison between parties

WordCloud for Democratic and Replublican

#functions for wordcloud
word_func <- function(var,value){
  cor <- VCorpus(VectorSource(data_frame[data_frame[var]==value,"text"]))
  cleaned <- cor %>% tm_map(removePunctuation)%>% tm_map(removeNumbers)%>%tm_map(removeWords,character(0))%>%tm_map(content_transformer(tolower))%>%tm_map(removeWords,stopwords('english'))%>%tm_map(stripWhitespace)%>%tm_map(removeWords,c("will","can","shall","upon","must","every","may","great"))
dict <- cleaned%>%tidy()%>%select(text)%>%unnest_tokens(dictionary,text)%>%anti_join(stop_words,by=c("dictionary"="word"))%>%group_by(dictionary)%>%count()%>%ungroup()%>%filter(dictionary!="NA")  
return(dict)
}
#wordCloud for the democratic party 
data1 = word_func("Party","Democratic")
data2 = word_func("Party","Republican")
wordcloud(data1$dictionary,data1$n,min.freq=3,max.words=80,random.order=FALSE, random.color=FALSE,colors=brewer.pal(8,"Dark2"),rot.per=.1)

#WordCloud for the Republican Party 
wordcloud(data2$dictionary,data2$n,min.freq=3,max.words=80,random.order=FALSE, random.color=FALSE,colors=brewer.pal(8,"Dark2"),rot.per=.1)

Top 10 Word Frequency for two parties

remove_plural <- function(word){
  gsub("s$","",word)
}
data("stop_words")
corpus <- VCorpus(VectorSource(data_frame$text))
corpus_cleaned <- corpus%>%tm_map(removePunctuation)%>%tm_map(removeNumbers)%>%tm_map(removeWords,character(0))%>%tm_map(content_transformer(tolower))%>%tm_map(removeWords,stopwords("english"))%>%tm_map(stripWhitespace)
corpus_tidy <- tidy(corpus_cleaned)%>%select(text)
completed <- corpus_tidy%>%mutate(president=data_frame$President,party=data_frame$Party,term=data_frame$Term)%>%unnest_tokens(dictionary,text)%>%anti_join(stop_words,by=c("dictionary"="word"))

completed$dictionary <- as.vector(sapply(completed$dictionary,remove_plural))
completed1 <- completed%>%filter(party %in% c("Democratic","Republican","Democratic-Republican Party"))
group <- completed1%>%group_by(dictionary,party)%>%count()
group_all <- completed1%>%group_by(dictionary)%>%count()%>%rename(all=n)
group %>% left_join(group_all,by="dictionary") %>% arrange(desc(all)) %>%head(30) %>%ungroup() %>%ggplot(aes(reorder(dictionary, all, FUN = min),n,fill=party))+geom_col()+xlab(NULL)+ylab("count")+coord_flip()+facet_wrap(~party)+theme(legend.position = "none")+ggtitle("Top 10 Word Frequency")

Fact 1: The top 5 words in presidents’ speeches are:“people”,“government”,“nation”,“world”,“country”; Replublican speaks the top 10 words more frequently than Democratic.

Step 2: Topic Modeling

dt <- completed%>%unite(doc,president,term)%>%count(doc,dictionary)
dtm <- cast_dtm(dt,doc,dictionary,n)
row_total <- apply(dtm, 1 ,sum)
dtm <- dtm[row_total>0,]
burnin <- 4000 # numbers we do not need 
iter <- 2000
thin <- 500 
seed <-list(2003,5,63,100001,765) # seed to start mcmc， reproducible
nstart <- 5
best <- TRUE

#Number of topics
k <- 5 #number of topics in anaylsis(may be a guess)

#Run LDA using Gibbs sampling
ldaOut <-LDA(dtm, k, method="Gibbs", control=list(nstart=nstart, seed = seed, best=best,burnin = burnin, iter = iter, thin=thin))

Visualize most frequent word for each topic

ldaOut%>%
  tidy() %>%
  group_by(topic) %>%
  top_n(8, beta) %>%
  ungroup() %>% mutate(term = reorder(term, beta))%>%
  ggplot(aes(term, beta, fill = factor(topic))) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +xlab(NULL)+ylab(NULL)+
  facet_wrap(~ topic, scales = "free_y")+
  coord_flip()+theme(legend.position = "None")

According to the words frequencies above, we assign topic1-topic5 as “government”,“world”,“public”,“america”,“law”;

#write out results
ldaOut_topics <- as.matrix(topics(ldaOut))
#table(c(1:k, ldaOut.topics))
write.csv(ldaOut_topics,file=paste("LDAGibbs",k,"DocsToTopics.csv"))
#top 6 terms in each topic
ldaOut_terms <- as.matrix(terms(ldaOut,20))
write.csv(ldaOut_terms,file=paste("LDAGibbs",k,"TopicsToTerms.csv"))
#probabilities associated with each topic assignment
topicProbabilities <- as.data.frame(ldaOut@gamma)
write.csv(topicProbabilities,file=paste("LDAGibbs",k,"TopicProbabilities.csv"))

Visulize the topic distribution for each party

t <- c("government","world","public","america","law")
topic_df <- data.frame(topic=t[as.vector(ldaOut_topics)],party=info$Party)
df1_demo <- topic_df[topic_df$party=="Democratic",]%>%group_by(topic)%>%count()%>%ungroup()%>%filter(topic!="NA")
df1_rep <- topic_df[topic_df$party=="Republican",]%>%group_by(topic)%>%count()%>%ungroup()%>%filter(topic!="NA")
n1 <- df1_demo$n
n2 <- df1_rep$n
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
waffle(c(america=n1[1],government=n1[2],law=n1[3],public=n1[4],word=n1[5]),rows=5,title="Democratic",size=0.5,glyph_size = 12,use_glyph = TRUE,pad=0)

waffle(c(america=n2[1],government=n2[2],law=n2[3],public=n2[4],word=n2[5]),rows=5,title="Republican",size=0.5,glyph_size = 12,use_glyph = TRUE,pad=0)

Fact 2: Democratic party talks more about “America”; Republican party talks more about “Public”;

Step 3: Clustering Analysis for presidents

colnames(topicProbabilities) <- c("government","world","public","america","law")
df_cluster <- cbind(topicProbabilities,info)%>%select(government,world,public,america,law,President,Term)%>%unite(id,President,Term)
rownames(df_cluster) <- df_cluster$id
cluster <- kmeans(scale(df_cluster[,1:5]),iter.max=200,5)

Clutering using Kmeans prediction

fviz_cluster(cluster,stand=T, repel= TRUE,
             data = df_cluster[,1:5],
             show.clust.cent=FALSE)

Fact 3: We see that Franklin D Roosvelt, William Cliton are in the same cluster, george washington_bush and Donald Trump are in the same cluster etc. The results indicates a potential relationship between speech topic and party.
